{# Shared Jinja macros used by every meeting-type template.

   The goal is that common cross-cutting rules (TL;DR, omit-empty, vendor
   injection, length mode, prior-action carryover, email draft, open
   questions, risks, confidentiality) live in ONE place and can be updated
   globally. Per-type templates only supply the sections unique to that
   meeting type.

   Conventions:
   - Every macro emits a self-contained block ending in one trailing blank
     line so templates can concatenate them freely.
   - Macros assume the caller already has `vendors`, `length_mode`,
     `prior_actions` in context when relevant — templates pass them through
     Jinja's variable scope.
#}

{%- macro omission_rule() -%}
**Omission rule:** If a section below would have no real content, OMIT THE ENTIRE HEADING AND BODY. Do not write "Not discussed", "None", "N/A", or any placeholder phrasing. A shorter document with only real content is always preferred over a padded one.
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro length_guidance(length_mode='concise') -%}
**Length guidance:**
{%- if length_mode == 'concise' %} Target ~150-400 words in Detailed Notes. An executive reader should be able to finish the minutes in under two minutes. Prefer tight bullets over prose where possible.
{%- elif length_mode == 'verbose' %} Target ~900-1500 words in Detailed Notes. Be comprehensive; include reasoning, trade-offs, alternatives, and open questions for each major topic.
{%- else %} Target ~400-900 words in Detailed Notes. Cover the reasoning and trade-offs behind each major topic without over-narrating.
{%- endif %}
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro tldr_block() -%}
## TL;DR (~100 words)
Write an executive digest at the very top of the output, before Summary. It MUST cover: the single biggest decision (or "no decisions"), the biggest risk or concern (or "no significant risks"), the most urgent action item and its owner, and the one thing a busy reader must take away. Cap at ~100 words. Do not pad — if nothing decision-worthy happened, say so in one sentence.
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro confidentiality_block() -%}
## Confidentiality
Classify the sensitivity of the discussion into exactly one of: `public`, `internal`, `confidential`, `restricted`. Populate the `confidentiality` structured field. When in doubt, err toward the higher classification.
- `public` — already public or suitable for any audience
- `internal` — standard company-internal; no sensitive data
- `confidential` — personnel, finance, customer, or unreleased product details
- `restricted` — legal, regulatory, board, security-incident, or M&A content
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro open_questions_block() -%}
## Open Questions
List questions raised during the meeting that were not resolved by the time it ended. Populate the `open_questions` structured field (each with `question`, `raised_by`, `owner` where identifiable). Omit this heading if no open questions remain.
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro risks_block() -%}
## Risks & Concerns
Capture substantive risks, warnings, or concerns raised by participants (technical, commercial, regulatory, people, security, timeline). Populate the `risks_and_concerns` structured field. Omit this heading if none were raised.
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro email_draft_block() -%}
## Follow-up Email Draft
Draft a short follow-up email the organizer can send to attendees. Populate the `email_draft` structured field:
- `subject` — under 10 words, specific
- `to` — attendee names
- `cc` — only if leadership, stakeholders, or affected teams should be looped in
- `body` — markdown, ~150 words max: one-line recap, bulleted decisions, bulleted action items with owner/due date, one-line closing
Omit entirely (leave `email_draft` null) if the meeting produced no commitments or decisions worth a follow-up.
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro vendor_feedback_block(vendors) -%}
## Vendor & Tooling Feedback
Capture feedback, pain points, feature requests, cost or performance issues about services and tools discussed. Omit this entire section (and all sub-headings) if no vendor or tool feedback was raised.
{% if vendors and vendors | length > 0 %}
{% for v in vendors %}
### {{ v }}
[Feedback on {{ v }}, if any — omit this sub-heading if nothing was said about {{ v }}]

{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
### Other Tools
[Jira, Slack, GitHub, CI/CD, monitoring, internal platforms, etc. — omit if no feedback.]
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro prior_actions_block(prior_actions) -%}
{% if prior_actions and prior_actions | length > 0 %}
## Prior Open Action Items (Carryover)
The following action items from previous meetings are still open. For each one that was acknowledged during THIS meeting as done, in progress, or dropped, populate an entry in the `prior_action_updates` structured field with the exact `action_item_id` shown, the new status (`done` | `in_progress` | `cancelled`), and a short evidence quote. Do NOT echo items that were not discussed.

{% for item in prior_actions %}
- **{{ item.id }}** — {{ item.description }}{% if item.owner %} · Owner: {{ item.owner }}{% endif %}{% if item.due_date %} · Due: {{ item.due_date }}{% endif %}{% if item.meeting_title %} · from "{{ item.meeting_title }}"{% endif %}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro meeting_header(kind, title, date, duration, attendees, organizer=None, attendee_join=', ') -%}
# {{ kind }}: {{ title }}

**Date:** {{ date }}
**Duration:** {{ duration }}
**Attendees:** {{ attendees | join(attendee_join) }}
{% if organizer %}**Organizer:** {{ organizer }}
{% endif %}
## Transcript
{{ transcript_text }}
{%- endmacro -%}

{%- macro closing_instructions(length_mode='concise') -%}
---

{{ omission_rule() }}

{{ length_guidance(length_mode) }}

Produce the minutes using ONLY the sections above that have real content. Populate every relevant structured field. Never fabricate information — only include what was actually said.
{%- endmacro -%}
